04421nam a22005775i 9780520930032DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209300327 a10.1525/97805209300322doi  a(DE-B1597)519155  a(OCoLC)55530289  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aAdrian, Bonnie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFraming the Bride :bGlobalizing Beauty and Romance in Taiwan's Bridal Industry /cBonnie Adrian. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (310 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Framings -- t1. How Can This Be? Ethnographic Contexts and History -- t2. Fantasy for Sale: The Modern Bridal Industry -- t3. Inner and Outer Worlds in Changing Taipei -- t4. Family Wedding Rites and Banquets -- t5. Making Up the Bride -- t6. Romance in the Photo Studio -- t7. Contextualizing Bridal Photos in Taiwan's Visual Culture -- t8. The Context of Looking: What Taipei Viewers See -- tConclusion: Reframings -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith a wedding impending, the Taiwanese bride-to-be turns to bridal photographers, makeup artists, and hair stylists to transform her image beyond recognition. They give her fairer skin, eyes like a Western baby doll, and gowns inspired by sources from Victorian England to MTV.An absorbing consideration of contemporary bridal practices in Taiwan, Framing the Bride shows how the lavish photographs represent more than mere conspicuous consumption. They are artifacts infused with cultural meaning and emotional significance, products of the gender- and generation-based conflicts in Taiwan's hybrid system of modern matrimony. From the bridal photographs, the book opens out into broader issues such as courtship, marriage, kinship, globalization, and the meaning of the "West" and "Western" cultural images of beauty.Bonnie Adrian argues that in compiling enormous bridal albums full of photographs of brides and grooms in varieties of finery, posed in different places, and exuding romance, Taiwanese brides engage in a new rite of passage-one that challenges the terms of marriage set out in conventional wedding rites. In Framing the Bride, we see how this practice is also a creative response to U.S. domination of transnational visual imagery-how bridal photographers and their subjects take the project of globalization into their own hands, defining its terms for their lives even as they expose the emptiness of its images.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBridal shopsxTaiwan. 0aBridal shopszTaiwan. 0aWedding photographyxTaiwanxTaiwan. 0aWedding photographyzTaiwan. 0aWedding supplies and services industryxTaiwan. 0aWedding supplies and services industryzTaiwan. 0aWeddingsxEquipment and suppliesxTaiwan. 0aWeddingszTaiwanxEquipment and supplies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520930032.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles